## 1. SCOPE AND OBJECTIVES

Analyze the FaaS application source code located in src/faas-app/ (git submodule
pointing to https://github.com/vifor/avp-petstore-sample-v2.git) and produce an
OpenAPI 3.0 specification covering all discoverable API endpoints, their HTTP
methods, path parameters, request/response schemas, and security requirements.

## 2. SOURCE FILES ANALYZED

The following files were read and analyzed (in discovery order):

  src/faas-app/amplify/backend/api/petstoreapi/cli-inputs.json
    → Authoritative API Gateway path registration (13 paths mapped to Lambdas)

  src/faas-app/amplify/backend/backend-config.json
    → Full dependency graph: 4 Lambda functions, 2 DynamoDB tables, Cognito
      User Pool, AVP Policy Store, API Gateway, SSM Parameter Store

  src/faas-app/amplify/backend/function/petstoreAdminStoreCrud/src/app.js
    → Express.js routes for /admin/store namespace
    → DynamoDB table: petstoreTenants (PK: id, SK: value)

  src/faas-app/amplify/backend/function/petstoreAdminFranchiseCrud/src/app.js
    → Express.js routes for /admin/franchise namespace
    → DynamoDB table: petstoreFranchise (PK: id, no sort key)

  src/faas-app/amplify/backend/function/petstoresample78b39c63/src/index.js
    → Store-operations Lambda: AVP authorization enforcer + actionMap
    → Source of truth for HTTP methods on /store/{storeId}/... paths

  src/faas-app/amplify/backend/function/petstoreAuthorizer/src/index.js
    → API Gateway Lambda Authorizer: Cognito JWT verification + AVP query
    → Entity construction and principal enrichment logic

  src/faas-app/amplify/backend/custom/petstoreAVPPolicyStore/assets/policySchema.json
    → Amazon Verified Permissions Cedar schema
    → Used to infer entity attributes for Pet, Order, Store, Franchise, User

  src/faas-app/amplify/backend/storage/petstoreTenants/cli-inputs.json
    → Confirms table structure: PK id (String), SK value (String)

  src/faas-app/amplify/backend/storage/petstoreFranchise/cli-inputs.json
    → Confirms table structure: PK id (String), no sort key

## 3. ENDPOINTS DISCOVERED

### 3.1 Store Operations (Lambda: petstoresample78b39c63)

All paths require both ApiKeyAuth (x-api-key header) and BearerAuth (Cognito JWT).
Authorization is enforced by AVP on every request via the petstoreAuthorizer Lambda.

  [GET]  /store/{storeId}/pets
         Action: SearchPets | Resource type: Store
         Response: PetList array

  [POST] /store/{storeId}/pet/create
         Action: AddPet | Resource type: Application
         Body: Pet object (partial, owner/store inferred at runtime)

  [POST] /store/{storeId}/pet/update/{petId}
         Action: UpdatePet | Resource type: Pet
         *** NOTE: HTTP method is POST, not PUT ***
         Body: Pet object (partial update)

  [GET]  /store/{storeId}/order/get/{orderNumber}
         Action: GetOrder | Resource type: Order

  [POST] /store/{storeId}/order/create
         Action: PlaceOrder | Resource type: Store
         Body: Order object

  [POST] /store/{storeId}/order/cancel/{orderNumber}
         Action: CancelOrder | Resource type: Order
         *** NOTE: HTTP method is POST, not DELETE ***

  [GET]  /store/{storeId}/orders
         Action: ListOrders | Resource type: Store
         Response: OrderList array

  [GET]  /store/{storeId}/inventory
         Action: GetStoreInventory | Resource type: Store
         Response: Inventory object

### 3.2 Admin Store Operations (Lambda: petstoreAdminStoreCrud)

  [GET]    /admin/store/{id}
           DynamoDB QueryCommand on petstoreTenants (PK = id)
           Returns all items with matching partition key

  [GET]    /admin/store/object/{id}/{value}
           DynamoDB GetItem on petstoreTenants (PK = id, SK = value)
           Returns single item

  [POST]   /admin/store
           DynamoDB PutItem — CREATE semantics
           Body: Store object

  [PUT]    /admin/store
           DynamoDB PutItem — UPDATE semantics (overwrite)
           Body: Store object

  [DELETE] /admin/store/object/{id}/{value}
           DynamoDB DeleteItem on petstoreTenants (PK = id, SK = value)

  [GAP]    GET /admin/store (list-all) is registered in API Gateway
           cli-inputs.json but NO Express handler exists in app.js.
           → Documented as a known implementation gap in the spec.

### 3.3 Admin Franchise Operations (Lambda: petstoreAdminFranchiseCrud)

  [GET]    /admin/franchise/{id}
           DynamoDB QueryCommand on petstoreFranchise (PK = id)

  [GET]    /admin/franchise/object/{id}
           DynamoDB GetItem on petstoreFranchise (PK = id)

  [POST]   /admin/franchise
           DynamoDB PutItem — CREATE semantics
           Body: Franchise object

  [PUT]    /admin/franchise
           DynamoDB PutItem — UPDATE semantics (overwrite)
           Body: Franchise object

  [DELETE] /admin/franchise/object/{id}
           DynamoDB DeleteItem on petstoreFranchise (PK = id)

  [GAP]    GET /admin/franchise (list-all) is registered in API Gateway
           cli-inputs.json but NO Express handler exists in app.js.
           → Documented as a known implementation gap in the spec.

## 4. SCHEMAS INFERRED

The FaaS store Lambda (petstoresample78b39c63) acts as a pure authorization
proxy — it delegates business logic to a downstream service and does not expose
the data model directly in its code. Schemas were inferred from two sources:

  a) AVP Cedar policy schema (policySchema.json):
     Defines entity types with typed attributes:
       - User: employmentStoreCodes (Set<Store>), employmentStoreFranchiseCodes (Set<StoreFranchise>)
       - Store: geo (String), memberOf StoreFranchise
       - StoreFranchise: stores (Set<Store>), name (String)
       - Pet: owner (User entity), store (Store entity)
       - Order: owner (User entity), store (Store entity)
       - Application: store (Store entity)

  b) DynamoDB table structures (cli-inputs.json files):
     petstoreTenants: PK id (String), SK value (String)  → Store model
     petstoreFranchise: PK id (String)                   → Franchise model

  LIMITATION: Pet and Order request/response bodies could not be fully inferred
  from static analysis. The downstream API that the store Lambda proxies to is
  not part of this repository. Schema definitions for Pet and Order in the
  generated spec are marked as best-effort approximations.

## 5. SECURITY MODEL DOCUMENTED

  Authentication:
    - Cognito User Pool JWT (id token) — validated in petstoreAuthorizer Lambda
    - API Key (x-api-key header) — validated by API Gateway

  Authorization:
    - Amazon Verified Permissions (Cedar ABAC) — every store operation request
      is evaluated against the policy store before execution
    - Entities passed to AVP: User (principal), Store/Franchise (resource context),
      Pet/Order (resource), Cognito Groups (principal parents)
    - SSM Parameter Store used for runtime retrieval of ApiKey and ApiRootUrl

  JWT claims used:
    - cognito:username → principal entityId
    - cognito:groups → Group membership
    - custom:franchiseCode → comma-separated StoreFranchise IDs
    - custom:employmentStoreCode → comma-separated Store IDs

## 6. GAPS AND ANOMALIES IDENTIFIED

  GAP-001: No GET /admin/store handler (list-all)
    API Gateway path registered in cli-inputs.json but no Express route handler
    exists in petstoreAdminStoreCrud/src/app.js.
    Impact: Route would return 404 or fall through to catch-all handler.

  GAP-002: No GET /admin/franchise handler (list-all)
    Same issue as GAP-001 for the franchise CRUD Lambda.

  GAP-003: HTTP method divergence — pet update uses POST
    /store/{storeId}/pet/update/{petId} is registered as POST in API Gateway
    and in the actionMap. RESTful convention would use PUT or PATCH.
    Impact: IaaS monolith uses PUT — this is a behavioral contract difference.

  GAP-004: HTTP method divergence — order cancel uses POST
    /store/{storeId}/order/cancel/{orderNumber} uses POST not DELETE.
    Impact: IaaS monolith uses DELETE — same behavioral contract difference.

  GAP-005: Pet and Order schemas are approximate
    The downstream service backing store operations is external to this repo.
    Full request/response payloads could not be verified from static analysis.

  GAP-006: No delete endpoint for Pet entity
    The actionMap references "DeletePet" in addResourceEntities() and
    buildResource() but no corresponding API Gateway path is registered in
    cli-inputs.json. The action exists in the authorization model but the
    route is unregistered.

  GAP-007: Admin paths have no AVP authorization
    Admin CRUD Lambdas (Store, Franchise) do not reference the AVP authorizer.
    These paths appear to rely solely on API key validation. This may be
    intentional (internal admin only) but is a security posture difference
    from the store operation paths.

## 7. OUTPUT ARTIFACTS

  docs/output/openapi.yaml
    Format    : OpenAPI 3.0.3
    Size      : ~700 lines YAML
    Endpoints : 19 path operations across 5 tag groups
    Schemas   : 14 component schemas
    Security  : ApiKeyAuth + BearerAuth defined and applied per operation
    Server    : AWS API Gateway URL template with apiId/region/stage variables
                (defaults: 5brhnloiod / sa-east-1 / main)

## 8. DECISIONS AND RATIONALE

  D1: Spec represents FaaS as-is (source of truth)
      HTTP methods documented exactly as implemented in the Lambda actionMap
      and API Gateway registration, even where they diverge from REST convention.
      Rationale: The spec must describe the current system, not an idealized one.
      Migration decisions about method normalization belong in Phase 3+.

  D2: List-all gaps documented, not filled
      Missing GET /admin/store and GET /admin/franchise handlers are flagged
      as gaps in the spec rather than silently adding placeholder operations.
      Rationale: Adding undocumented/unimplemented paths would misrepresent the
      current FaaS contract.

  D3: Pet/Order schemas marked as approximate
      Rather than omitting schemas entirely, approximate definitions were
      provided based on AVP entity attributes, with explicit documentation
      of the inference source and limitation.
      Rationale: Partial schema is more useful than no schema for migration
      planning. Gaps are clearly flagged.

  D4: Admin paths given x-api-key only security
      Store operation paths apply both ApiKeyAuth and BearerAuth.
      Admin paths apply only ApiKeyAuth (matches observed Lambda code).

## 9. REPRODUCTION STEPS

To regenerate docs/output/openapi.yaml from scratch:
  1. Ensure src/faas-app submodule is initialized and checked out
     git submodule update --init --recursive
  2. Submit the prompt at prompts/phase1-api-discovery/generate-openapi.txt
     to an LLM with access to this repository
  3. Verify output against this log for completeness

## 10. NEXT RECOMMENDED STEPS

  Phase 2 — IaaS Contract Analysis
    Analyze NestJS monolith (src/monolith-app/) to produce equivalent OpenAPI
    spec, then diff against docs/output/openapi.yaml to identify migration gaps.

  Phase 3 — Contract Reconciliation
    For each divergence identified (HTTP methods, path structures, schemas),
    define migration strategy: adapt IaaS to match FaaS contract, or update
    clients to use new IaaS contract.

  Address GAP-003 and GAP-004 (method divergence):
    Decide whether IaaS should accept POST for update/cancel to maintain
    backward compatibility, or whether clients will be updated.

  Address GAP-006 (DeletePet unregistered):
    Determine if DeletePet should be implemented and registered in IaaS.

